hopobject.body: How long are you planning to stay here? mtg invigorate infect And yet even in a lofty genre like the symphony, the ancient roots of song and dance keep reappearing, like an underground river suddenly popping up. Think of the Adagietto from Mahler’s Fifth Symphony (the one made famous in Death in Venice). Isn’t that an example of “disguised song”, with the violins taking the place of voices? Echoes of the dance are even more common, lingering on right through the 19th century and into the 20th, usually in the form of that fast triple-time movement called a scherzo.
